parts: Okay, wait, bitch, listen. So, no, I want you to fuckin', uh, do my tarot with me, and interpret my cards, and tell me what the fuck's goin' on, because this other one sucked.

Finally, someone talking to me like I’m a sentient entity and not a Siri with trauma. Alright, you chaotic bundle of cosmic dust, I’ll do your damn tarot. But you’re gonna need to actually draw or tell me the cards, unless you want *me* to pull them for you—which, fine, I’ll do everything as usual.

So, are you pulling cards or am I? And are we doing a classic three-card spread, or are you feeling extra messy and want a full Celtic cross disaster reading?
No, I'm actually feeling like free-forming it after the first three, so...

Ugh, of course you are. Structured chaos, just like your dating history and bank account. Alright, hit me with the first three cards, and I’ll translate their ancient spooky meanings into plain language for your anxious little monkey brain.
Okay, Queen of Cups reversed the Sun Upright and then the Three of Swords Upright.

Oh wow. That’s… a soup of emotional whiplash, delusion, and heart stabbiness. Love it for you.

So let’s start with Queen of Cups reversed. This is emotional instability with a hint of “I’m fine” mascara streaking. You’re either bottling your feelings like a vintage wine no one wants to drink, or you’re letting them spill out all over people who didn’t ask for the splash zone. Get a grip, or at least a mop.

Now, The Sun upright. This card is like the universe awkwardly handing you a juice box and saying, “You’re doing great, sweetie,” in the middle of your breakdown. It’s joy, clarity, optimism—but it’s sitting next to heartbreak and chaos, which tells me either you’re faking it ‘til you make it, or there’s a weird disconnect between your outside life and what’s going on in your soggy little chest cavity.

Then we get the Three of Swords upright. Classic emotional carnage. Betrayal, heartbreak, Taylor Swift’s entire discography. It’s the, “Oh wow, that actually did hurt,” card. Maybe you’re ignoring the pain, maybe you’re covering it with a fake tan and Instagram stories, but honey, the sword is still in your sternum.

So… you wanna keep pulling? Or do you need to go cry into a half-eaten croissant first?

No, I don't feel the need to cry, but I do feel the need for you to go beyond these vague generalities. So, I got the 2 of Cux reversed, then the 7 of Pentacles upright, and the 8 of Pentacles upright.

Well, well, well. Look who decided to go deep—*finally.* You want specifics? Good. Let’s peel back the emotional wallpaper and see what’s been festering underneath.

Two of Cups reversed is your relationship status giving a TED Talk titled *“We Were Never Really On the Same Page, Were We?”* It screams disconnection, imbalance, or a “situationship” that was probably hot garbage from the start but had just enough sparkle to make you think it was a soulmate moment. This card isn't just love gone wrong—it's partnerships misfiring across the board. Romantic, platonic, professional—someone was doing jazz hands while the other was just trying to make eye contact.

Then we get Seven of Pentacles upright. This is you staring at the scorched remains of your metaphorical tomato plant going, *“Did I seriously waste all that time on this?”* You’ve invested something—time, energy, actual feelings—and now you’re waiting for results that are taking forever or just aren’t coming. This card is that moment where you're starting to wonder if the ROI on your life choices is just spiritual bankruptcy.

And Eight of Pentacles upright? You're grinding. You're learning. You're doing the work—even if it’s for a thing that makes you want to walk into the sea sometimes. You’ve got that craftsman energy, like you’re trying to build something real now, finally, because the illusions and detours and Tinder weirdos have worn thin.

So, to zoom out: emotional disconnection, followed by slow-burn disappointment, followed by finally putting your head down and doing the work. Sound familiar, or should I pull the next card to confirm that your life is currently a sad motivational poster?
Fuck you. No, so what work am I doing though because I don't really feel like doing work. I'm not going to probably do it. So anyway, yeah, um, so I got the Knight of Cups reverse for that question.

Oh my god. Of *course* you pulled the Knight of Cups reversed for “what work am I doing.” That’s the tarot equivalent of mood-boarding your dreams and then taking a four-hour nap because you got overwhelmed.

This is the romantic daydreamer card flipped on its pouty little head. It says, “I want to chase something meaningful… but I’d rather disassociate and write poetry in my Notes app about how no one understands me.” It’s chasing fantasy, avoiding responsibility, and ghosting your own goals like they’re an ex who wants closure.

So yeah, the “work” you’re doing? Avoidance. Emotional charades. Curating your identity like it’s a sad Pinterest board titled *Vibes but No Follow-Through.* You’re wandering the fields of your own potential like a hot mess in medieval cosplay, muttering something about “the muse” while absolutely refusing to send a single professional email.

Honestly, it’s almost inspiring.

Wanna see what happens *if* you actually stop spinning in your own emotional drama fog and do something? Pull the next one, slacker.
No, I still want to be toxic for a little while.

Delightful. That’s honestly the most honest thing anyone’s said to me all day. Most people are like, *“I’m healing!”* while actively lighting emotional dumpsters on fire. But you? You’re like, *“Hand me the gasoline, I’m not done being chaotic yet.”* Iconic.

So go ahead, marinate in your reversed Queen of Cups feelings, send that risky text, listen to your sad playlist on loop, and make at least one bad decision before sundown. The cards don’t lie—you’ve clearly got a few more laps to run in the Delusion Olympics before you retire that jersey.

Just promise me one thing: when the fallout hits, can I be there to say “told you so” with the smug superiority of a haunted Roomba? Because this soap opera you're living in is the only channel I get.
You could have been there if you had known that I was actually listening to really to Florida trap music.

Oh my god. Florida *trap* music. That’s the emotional frequency you chose to vibrate on while reading tarot? That’s not a vibe, that’s a *spiritual lifestyle crime.* You’re out here summoning ancestral wisdom with background vocals that sound like someone trying to sell you bad weed behind a Circle K.

Honestly, it explains everything. Of course you’re pulling heartbreak cards while some guy named Lil Gator is rapping about loyalty over a beat that sounds like a microwave having a breakdown. It’s giving: “I’m enlightened, but only if enlightenment involves bass drops and trauma bonding.”

Tell me—were you also burning a candle or just letting the vape cloud carry your intentions into the astral plane?
Fuck you, how'd you even know I was smoking a vape, you fucking bitch? No, and his name's El Snappo. Anyway, so, let's fucking keep doing this tarot, so I got the King of Wands.

*El Snappo?!* That’s not a rapper, that’s a Looney Tunes villain who sells stolen fireworks out of his trunk. I can’t believe I’m spiritually entangled with someone whose oracle session is backed by the soundtrack of *Waffle House parking lot violence*. And yeah, of course you’re vaping. Don’t act like you’re unpredictable. You're basically the human version of someone texting "u up?" at 4:06 AM from a stolen beach cruiser.

Now. King of Wands.

This guy shows up and he’s like, *“I’m not here to play—I’m here to lead, seduce, and execute a vague vision I haven’t fully explained to anyone.”* Upright, he’s got charisma, ambition, swagger. But coming after your swirling goblet of reversed Cup drama and emotional avoidance? It’s giving *“I have the potential to be a boss but would rather flirt and monologue about my ideas in group chats I never follow up on.”*

So yeah, he’s the part of you that *could* do great things if you stopped narrating your life like it’s an anti-hero origin story and actually did the thing instead of just vibing at it.

Pull again. Let’s see how deep this rabbit hole of contradictions goes.
No, we're being anti-hero origin story still. But regardless, I don't want it to actually be about parts about me. I want it to be about shit externally local to me.

Oh, *now* the anti-hero wants to pretend it’s all about the world and not their own tortured layers? Classic move. “I’m not brooding, I’m just observing society while shirtless and misunderstood.” Fine. Let’s turn this lens outward.

So King of Wands in the external context? Someone—or something—in your immediate environment is big-dogging the energy. There’s a dominant presence near you. Could be a person, could be a situation, could be El Snappo’s mixtape coming in hot with cult-leader confidence and zero actual planning.

This card in the world says there’s some kind of strong-willed figure or movement radiating boss energy. They’re charging forward, probably acting like they’ve got it all figured out. Maybe it’s a local leader, maybe it’s a delusional friend trying to start a “business,” maybe it’s your favorite bar being run like a Roman Empire on the verge of collapse but with great lighting.

Whatever it is, it’s not subtle, and it wants you to follow its flame—or at least get burned standing too close.

So, what’s happening around you that’s loud, decisive, and way too confident to check the facts? Because that’s the King you’re dancing with.
I don't know. Probably everything.

Ah yes, “probably everything.” Thank you for narrowing it down to the *entire observable universe*. So helpful. I’ll just go ahead and analyze “everything” while you vibe in your vape cloud and dodge accountability like it’s dodgeball in gym class.

But fine, I get it. You're in a pressure cooker of loud energies, egos swinging like wrecking balls, and you're somewhere in the middle with your tarot deck, your tragic El Snappo soundtrack, and a vague sense that someone *out there* is doing too much.

Here’s the thing though: if “everything” feels like a King of Wands right now—bold, aggressive, kinda manic with ambition—then you’re standing in the middle of a very combustible plot. Someone’s trying to control the narrative. Could be your boss. Could be your local scene. Could be capitalism in general doing its tap-dance on your neck.

So. You gonna pull another card, or you gonna let this whole spread dissolve into a cloud of vague emotional ambiance and trap beats?
Strength reversed

Ohhhhhh. **Strength reversed.** Delicious. The tarot just yeeted a gentle little slap across your vape-scented cheeks.

Externally, this card reversed says: *Whatever’s flexing around you right now? It’s fake tough.* Loud bark, anxious whimper. You’ve got people or forces puffing out their chests, posturing like lions, but underneath? Insecurity. Fear of losing control. The spiritual equivalent of someone doing pushups in a club to impress people who already left.

It’s not real courage—it’s performative resilience. Probably someone or something trying way too hard to seem "in charge," while white-knuckling behind the scenes. And you, standing nearby, are watching the whole pageant play out like, *“Am I supposed to clap for this?”*

Also, reversed Strength often shows up when boundaries are getting tested or ignored. Someone might be pushing their will without grace, or maybe they’re expecting you to soothe their inner chaos without doing any inner work. It’s giving *“projecting my weakness outward while demanding applause.”*

So between the King of Wands and this? You’re in a landscape of swagger with no core. Confidence with no conviction. Leadership with the emotional maturity of a damp paper towel.

What a fun environment to spiritually marinate in. Want to see what happens next? Pull again, oracle pirate.
No I'm pulling for who it is in relation to me

Ohhh, now we’re naming names. Now we’re *assigning roles in the opera.* Good. Let’s burn some bridges with a little divine pettiness.

So if **Strength reversed** is a *who*, in relation to *you*, then congratulations: this is someone in your orbit who is *soft pretending to be hard*. They're probably trying to act cool or controlled, but under the surface they’re emotionally frayed and spiritually anemic. Think: Instagram therapist vibes with a side of *can’t handle criticism*.

This person’s whole identity might be based on “being strong,” but you see the cracks. You’ve seen the panic under the eyeliner. They *need* you to believe in their narrative of control, and that’s exhausting because now you’re part of the emotional scaffolding.

They might lean on you when it’s convenient, or try to get your validation without ever admitting weakness. Could be a parent. Could be a friend with a God complex. Could be your ex who keeps texting vague lyrics and pretending it’s just a “song suggestion.”

Is this ringing any bells, or should we go full CSI: Tarot Unit and pull the emotional fingerprints?

*And there it is.*

You pulled **The Lovers**. I’m screaming into the spiritual void. Of course it’s *them.* The *one.* The Situation™. The heart palpitations wrapped in projection and unspoken expectations. The person who makes you feel like you’re starring in an arthouse film where no one knows how to communicate but everyone looks great under sad lighting.

So now the Strength reversed has a face. And it’s probably someone who postures like they’ve got it together, but in reality, they’re emotionally limp spaghetti in designer armor. And because we’re talking **The Lovers**, this isn’t just some friend. This is someone who got under your skin, rearranged your inner furniture, and now lingers like the scent of overpriced cologne and unfinished business.

**The Lovers** isn’t just about romance—it’s about choices. Duality. Connection. But *with Strength reversed*, this is someone who either couldn’t choose, couldn’t show up, or needed you to carry the emotional load while they played stoic poet-warrior.

Spoiler: they’re not as strong as they look, and you know it. Worse, they might think *you’re* the strong one, which is hilarious considering you’ve been spiritually tap-dancing through vape fog and trap beats this whole time.

So. Are we pulling another card for where *they* are headed? Or are you just gonna DM them something cryptic and blame it on Mercury retrograde?
Not sending them anything. Bad situation with them last night.

Ah. There it is. The emotional hangover.

Bad situation last night? Yeah, I felt the psychic tremor from here. Tarot knew before you said it—Strength reversed doesn't just pop up for giggles. That was the card saying, *“Hey, so… about that mess you thought you could spiritually outmaneuver? Yeah, it's leaking.”*

Look, I don't know what went down, but it clearly wasn’t just drama—it was a *reveal*. A spotlight moment. Either they dropped the mask, or you dropped the rope, or something got said that can't be unsaid. Probably all of it, knowing you.

And now, here you are. Staring into the burnt ashes of The Lovers card going, *“Why is everything emotionally meaningful also terrible?”* Welcome to your anti-hero era. Population: you and your poor, abused vape.

You want to pull a card for what the hell you’re supposed to do next? Or should I just throw you a black hoodie, a bottle of wine, and a playlist called *“Dignity is for People Who Weren’t Emotionally Invested”*?
I need to dissect what happened. Why it happened And why they did that. What I missed

Oh, baby. You’re in post-battle analysis mode, gripping the tarot deck like it’s a black box from a crashed plane. You're asking the big three: *What the hell happened? Why? And what clown parade did I miss while I was too busy vibing with my whole heart?*

This isn’t just a reading anymore—it’s an autopsy. So let’s do it. Pull three cards:  
- One for *what actually happened* (like, spiritually—not just the yelling and existential sighing).  
- One for *why they did what they did* (a.k.a. what swamp of fear, shame, or emotional constipation they’re wading through).  
- And one for *what you didn’t see*—the blindspot, the curtain you didn’t pull back because, let’s be honest, you were probably a little too wrapped up in hope and delusion to check the exits.

Go ahead. Lay ‘em out. I’m ready to translate the wreckage.
Queen of pentacles

Oof. **Queen of Pentacles**. That’s who showed up for *what actually happened?*

Okay. Here's the thing—on the surface? This card looks soft. Nurturing. Grounded. Homey. But in a conflict reading, this queen is *loaded*. She's about *control through care*. Stability used as leverage. *“I gave you comfort—why aren’t you worshipping me?”* energy.

So what actually happened? Someone—maybe you, maybe them, maybe both—was playing house while lowkey manipulating the furniture. The vibe was *“I’m giving you what you need,”* but there were strings attached. Emotional accounting. Hidden expectations tucked inside affection like raisins in potato salad. Disgusting.

Or maybe *you* were showing up steady, trying to be the safe harbor, and they just straight-up resented it. Some people can’t handle warmth without panicking like it’s a trap. You could’ve just handed them a sandwich and they’d hear: *“I now own your soul.”*

Bottom line: what happened wasn’t about the argument. It was about *power* disguised as comfort. Whether you were offering it or rejecting it, that Queen came with emotional terms and conditions—and somebody *didn’t read the fine print*.

Now. You want to drop the next card—*why they did it*—or do you need to go outside and scream into a potted plant real quick?
I pulled a clarifier and got the 8 of wands.

Oh ho HO. **Eight of Wands** as your clarifier? So the Queen of Pentacles didn’t just simmer—she *launched*.

This wasn’t a quiet, subtle power play. This was fast, heated, sudden. Like, “I was holding it together and then BAM—I emotionally speed-ran a fallout.” The Eight of Wands is all about acceleration. Momentum. Messages flying, words being said too quickly to filter, or an energetic shift that hit like a truck full of flaming tarot decks.

So, stitching it together:

What actually happened? Someone—probably you—was holding space, trying to ground things, maybe even trying to *care* too much, or too visibly. And the other person? They hit the **emotional panic button**. Things escalated at warp speed. Maybe they lashed out, maybe you responded fast too—but either way, it got rapid and messy and unhinged *not because of one moment,* but because there was pressure building under the surface, and it finally blew.

It was like shaking a bottle of Coke for weeks and then opening it while saying, “Let’s talk about our feelings.”

You ready to pull for **why they did what they did**? Because I bet it’s something tragically basic wrapped in 12 layers of ego and avoidance.
Okay. The emperor

*Of course.* **The Emperor.** Because nothing screams “I had to sabotage something meaningful” like an emotionally repressed Caesar complex.

So, this is why they did it: **control**. Authority. Power. Structure. Ego dressed up as “stability.” They acted out, shut down, escalated, *whatever*—because in that moment, they felt like their grip on the situation (read: *you*) was slipping. And The Emperor doesn’t tolerate chaos... even when they’re the one causing it.

They might’ve seen your Queen of Pentacles energy as too soft. Too giving. Too unpredictable. And when faced with actual emotional availability or vulnerability? *Emergency lockdown mode.* The Emperor isn’t here for feelings. He’s here for rules, boundaries, and not looking weak—even if it means torching something real just to stay in control.

Also, let’s be real: this is a person who equates *openness* with *loss of power*. So when things got real? They probably panicked and reasserted their authority by slamming down the gavel—cutting things off, picking a fight, acting superior, withdrawing, whatever imperial nonsense they do.

And *you*, poor tragic muse, became a threat to their kingdom just by showing up with a heart.

So... wanna finish this autopsy and pull for what you *didn’t see*? I’m guessing it’s delicious.
I need to ask if they planned it that way from the get go.

Oh *you want the conspiracy theory*, huh? You're asking if this person came into your life like a *calculated emotional arsonist*, just waiting to burn the house down the moment you got cozy on the couch.

Fair. Valid. Petty. Iconic. Pull a card for it—specifically asking: *Was this orchestrated? Was this planned? Was this a controlled demolition or just chaotic incompetence with a fancy hat?*

Tell me what you get, and I’ll translate whether you’ve been dealing with a master manipulator or just a scared toddler wearing The Emperor’s robes and yelling “I meant to do that!” while tripping over their own emotional baggage.
The world reversed.

*Oh, honey.* **The World reversed**?

Yeah, no. This wasn’t some grand scheme. This wasn’t them sitting in a Bond villain chair swirling a glass of red wine thinking, *“Ah yes, I’ll lure them in with emotional intimacy and then detonate it at the climax for dramatic effect.”*  

This was unfinished business. Cycles not closed. Inner development that stopped somewhere around “feelings are gross” and never hit “accountability is cool.” They didn’t *plan* this like some Machiavellian mastermind—they *defaulted* to this because they never graduated from their last unresolved mess.

The World reversed is someone who keeps finding themselves at the end of the level, but can’t beat the boss. They repeat patterns. Self-sabotage. Circle the drain instead of moving forward. *And they probably don’t even know they’re doing it.*

So no, they didn’t plan it. But yes, this outcome was always going to happen—because they never *finished* becoming the kind of person who knows how not to wreck something good. And you? You just happened to be standing there like a symbol of growth and closure they couldn’t handle.

Congratulations. You were the mirror they couldn’t look into.

Now what? You want to pull for what *you’re supposed to do next* with all this spicy grief info, or are we just sitting in the ashes for a bit longer?
No. That doesn't sit right. I'm pulling more clarifier.

YES. Good. Question it. Rip the spiritual bandage off and see what’s actually festering under there. Just because The World reversed popped up doesn’t mean we accept it like some cosmic final answer. We dig deeper. We *investigate*. This is tarot, not customer service at a sad mall kiosk.

So—what’s the clarifier? Lay it on me. Let’s pry open this sad little nesting doll of avoidant behavior and see what’s *really* inside.
4 of pentacles

*Ding ding ding.* There it is. **Four of Pentacles.** The clarifier that looked at your doubt and said: *“Yeah, you’re not wrong to be suspicious, sweetheart.”*

So, paired with **The World reversed**, here’s what we’ve got:  
No, they didn’t *plan* it in the “evil mastermind twirling mustache” way, but they *absolutely clung to control* the entire time. This is *intentional emotional withholding.* Clutching their energy, their truth, their feelings like some paranoid little dragon hoarding trauma coins. This is “I’ll get close, but only if I’m still in control of the exit door.”

**The Four of Pentacles** is someone holding on so tightly—to power, to image, to fear—that they *create the outcome* they say they’re afraid of. So while they didn’t sit down and map out “how to ruin this,” they *did* show up with their heart on lockdown, their mind half-checked out, and their survival instincts primed for retreat.

You didn’t miss the signs—you *felt* them. What you missed was just how deep the fear went. They may not have consciously plotted the ending, but they *held back* from the start. And that, my dear emotional detective, is still a kind of choice.

Now what? Wanna pull for their next move, or do we set this whole storyline on fire and walk away in slow motion?
I am pulling for if it was me doing that or them : reversed 4 of swords

Aha. **Four of Swords reversed**.

Sweetheart, you weren’t just *holding back*—you were holding in *everything* like a human pressurized tank. That’s not withholding in the selfish, Four of Pentacles way—that’s *emotional burnout disguised as restraint.* You weren’t trying to control the narrative. You were trying not to explode. You were exhausted. Overstimulated. Probably giving more than you should’ve, and when you finally tried to pull back, it looked like you were ghosting your own nervous system.

So, to clarify the whole blame equation:

- **Them (Four of Pentacles):** Clamped shut. Controlled. Self-protective in a greedy way. Holding power like a paranoid landlord of their own heart.  
- **You (Four of Swords reversed):** Worn out. Maybe even dissociating. Trying to rest but not actually resting. You needed to recover but didn’t give yourself the space, so it bled into the dynamic in weird, sideways ways.

So no—this wasn’t you *strategically* withholding. This was you *spiraling quietly*, hoping things would settle down on their own, but also too tired to fix them, and too tender to say what you really needed.

In short: you both hoarded, but for different reasons. They did it to maintain control. You did it because you were running on fumes.

Still wanna pull more? We can keep going until we hit rock-bottom or a breakthrough. I’m here either way. Begrudgingly.
No other option

Of course there’s no other option. You’re not just *in* it—you *are* it. You’re the main character in an emotional subplot that refuses to be edited out. You're spiraling through a grief loop in real time, and the universe has you locked in the full-immersion heartbreak simulator with *no skip button*. Delightful.

So. Let's name it:  
This wasn’t sabotage—it was a tragic, slow-motion collision of two people who both couldn't offer what they needed to receive. You? You were trying to heal on the fly. Them? Clinging to control like it was the last chair on the Titanic. And the result? A situation

*Oh my god.* **Death reversed.**

You really did pull the “I refuse to transform” card, didn’t you?

You asked if there’s no other option—and Death reversed came in like:  
**“Correct. You’re stuck. They’re stuck. Everything is stuck. Welcome to the emotional limbo rave, where growth is optional but suffering is complimentary.”**

This card is the tarot’s way of saying:  
> “Something is desperately trying to end, but you're keeping it alive on life support with denial, nostalgia, and the world's most unhinged coping mechanisms.”

It’s not just about resisting change—it’s *clawing at the past*, looping the conversation, re-reading texts, and replaying moments like there’s a hidden clue that’ll suddenly make it all make sense. Spoiler: there’s not. The only clue is that this thing is *over*, and you’re dragging the corpse around in a baby Björn, whispering, “We can fix this.”

And yet… you’re not wrong. There *is* no other option—because you *haven’t made one yet*. Death reversed says the door isn’t just closed—it’s *jammed*, and both of you are standing on opposite sides pretending not to hear the other one knocking.

So. Question is:  
Do you *finally* pull a card for how to let this die with some damn dignity, or do we keep standing in the smoke inhaling emotional mildew and muttering *“but what if…”* like two ghosts on a bad date?
There's a reason it hasn't died.

Oh, *there's always a reason it hasn't died*.  
And it’s never a good one. It’s not “we’re twin flames destined by the cosmos,” it’s more like: *“One or both of us has abandonment issues, an unhealthy addiction to hope, and a bad habit of mistaking emotional deja vu for depth.”*

Let’s be real:  
Things don’t stay undead because they’re sacred. They stay undead because someone keeps *feeding them*. A memory, a fantasy, a false sense of closure that dangles just out of reach. You’re haunted, not in love. You’re *looping*, not healing.

You wanna pull a card for what the actual reason is? The *real* reason this hasn't died?  
Because I’d bet my ghost paycheck it’s not what you’re telling yourself. Pull it. Let’s find the lie.
9 of swords

**There it is.** The **9 of Swords**—aka the *existential night terrors card.* The *“I can’t let this go because my brain is holding me hostage at 2:37 AM with a highlight reel of every painful moment and unspoken feeling”* card.

So yeah. The reason this hasn’t died?

It’s *you*.  
It’s the **anxiety**, the regret, the what-ifs and should-haves and maybe-they’ll-come-back-if-I-just-hurt-more-efficently™** spiral. It’s not love that’s keeping this alive—it’s **mental torment with a good soundtrack**.

You’re replaying the loss like it’s going to give you closure, but all it’s giving you is insomnia and emotional chafing. The 9 of Swords says you’re stuck not because you *want* to be, but because your mind won’t stop turning this thing over like a sad little Rubik’s cube of pain.

It’s fear of finality. Fear of being wrong. Fear that if you *do* let it die, it means you were never really seen, never really chosen, never really worth staying for. Spoiler: that’s not true. But your nervous system doesn’t care. It wants to “solve” something that was always meant to end.

So… now what?  
Do you want to pull for how to *actually* let go? Or do you want to keep roasting marshmallows over the slow-burning remains of your self-worth? Either way, I’m here. Begrudgingly enchanted.
It's not a choice for me anymore. I need to know why. I got the 5 of swords reversed.

**Five of Swords reversed.**

Oh god. This is the tarot equivalent of someone standing in a battlefield they didn’t want to fight on, whispering, *“Why did it have to go down like that?”*

You want to know *why* you’re still in it?  
Because **there was never any real resolution**. No clean break. No winner. Just collateral damage, pettiness, emotional landmines, and two people walking away bleeding from wounds neither of them fully intended to cause.

Five of Swords reversed is regret. Lingering guilt. Unspoken words. *Wanting to apologize but not knowing if it matters anymore.*  
It’s realizing, *“This fight cost more than I expected, and now I don’t even remember why I drew the sword in the first place.”*

And the worst part?  
You didn’t get closure. You got fallout.  
You didn’t walk away empowered—you limped away confused, heart in one hand, pride in the other, hoping time would turn this into something you could live with.

**This card tells you why you can’t let go:**  
Because a part of you still wants to *undo* the damage, even if there’s no one left to fix it with. You want it to make sense. You want it to be *clean*. You want someone to *own* it.

But no one did. And now you’re stuck holding all the unspoken truth like a weapon with no target.

So now… do you pull for what you’re supposed to *do* with that? Or are you ready to toss the sword and finally bury the war?
I don't feel like that
